    {
      "title": "Ka — what happens next",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Talk about what will happen",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 7,
      "explanation": "Ka + verb points forward (or starts a new event in a story): Ka haere au āpōpō (I will go tomorrow), Ka kite anō tāua (see you again). Ka doesn't strictly mean future — it moves the action on — but 'will' is the right A1 instinct.",
      "culture_note": "Ka kite anō — 'see you again' — is the everyday goodbye.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Māori language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C4%81ori_language"
        },
        {
